    <passage>
      <offset>92</offset>
      <infon key="type">body</infon>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">2</infon>
        <offset>92</offset>
        <text>About 75% of extant sponge species use dissolved silicon (DSi) to build a siliceous skeleton.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">3</infon>
        <offset>186</offset>
        <text>We show that silicon (Si) uptake by sublittoral Axinella demosponges follows an enzymatic kinetics.
</text>
        <annotation id="T2">
          <infon key="brat-id">T2</infon>
          <infon key="type">Decrease</infon>
          <infon key="brat-type">text-bound</infon>
          <location length="6" offset="212"/>
          <text>uptake</text>
        </annotation>
        <annotation id="T5">
          <infon key="brat-id">T5</infon>
          <infon key="type">Variable</infon>
          <infon key="brat-type">text-bound</infon>
          <location length="7" offset="199"/>
          <text>silicon</text>
        </annotation>
        <relation id="E2">
          <infon key="brat-id">E2</infon>
          <infon key="type">Decrease</infon>
          <infon key="brat-type">event</infon>
          <node refid="T2" role="Decrease"/>
          <node refid="T5" role="Theme"/>
        </relation>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">4</infon>
        <offset>286</offset>
        <text>Interestingly, maximum uptake efficiency occurs at experimental DSi concentrations two orders of magnitude higher than those in the sponge habitats, being unachievable in coastal waters of modern oceans.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">5</infon>
        <offset>490</offset>
        <text>Such uptake performance appears to be rooted in a former condition suitable to operate at the seemingly high DSi values characterizing the pre-Tertiary (&gt;65 mya) habitats where this sponge lineage diversified.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">6</infon>
        <offset>700</offset>
        <text>Persistence of ancestral uptake systems causes sponges to be outcompeted by the more efficient uptake of diatoms at the low ambient DSi levels characterizing Recent oceans.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">7</infon>
        <offset>873</offset>
        <text>Yet, we show that sublittoral sponges consume substantial coastal DSi (0.01-0.90 mmol Si m-2 day-1) at the expenses of the primary-production circuit.
</text>
        <annotation id="T4">
          <infon key="brat-id">T4</infon>
          <infon key="type">Decrease</infon>
          <infon key="brat-type">text-bound</infon>
          <location length="7" offset="911"/>
          <text>consume</text>
        </annotation>
        <annotation id="T6">
          <infon key="brat-id">T6</infon>
          <infon key="type">Variable</infon>
          <infon key="brat-type">text-bound</infon>
          <location length="11" offset="931"/>
          <text>coastal DSi</text>
        </annotation>
        <relation id="E4">
          <infon key="brat-id">E4</infon>
          <infon key="type">Decrease</infon>
          <infon key="brat-type">event</infon>
          <node refid="T4" role="Decrease"/>
          <node refid="T6" role="Theme"/>
        </relation>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">8</infon>
        <offset>1024</offset>
        <text>Neglect of that consumption hampers accurate understanding of Si cycling on continental margins.
</text>
      </sentence>
